  "text": "Service account token auto-mounting in Kubernetes is controlled by three main components:\n\n1. ADMISSION CONTROLLER (plugin/pkg/admission/serviceaccount/admission.go): The ServiceAccount admission plugin implements MutationInterface and ValidationInterface. When a pod is created, the Admit() method checks whether to auto-mount the service account token by calling shouldAutomount(), which evaluates pod.Spec.AutomountServiceAccountToken and serviceAccount.AutomountServiceAccountToken fields (defaulting to true for backward compatibility). If auto-mounting is enabled, mountServiceAccountToken() adds volume mounts to all containers and creates a Projected volume with the TokenVolumeSource(), which includes: (a) ServiceAccountToken projection for the actual JWT token, (b) ConfigMap projection for the kube-root-ca.crt certificate, and (c) DownwardAPI projection for the namespace. These are mounted to /var/run/secrets/kubernetes.io/serviceaccount.\n\n2. TOKEN CONTROLLER (pkg/controller/serviceaccount/tokens_controller.go): The TokensController watches ServiceAccount and Secret resources to manage service account token secrets. When a pod's service account needs a token secret, the controller's generateTokenIfNeeded() method (called from syncSecret()) generates the actual JWT token using the Claims() function and stores it in the secret's data fields (token, ca.crt, namespace). The controller maintains the token secrets as service accounts are created, updated, and deleted.\n\n3. SERVICE ACCOUNTS CONTROLLER (pkg/controller/serviceaccount/serviceaccounts_controller.go): Creates default service accounts in every namespace via syncNamespace(). This ensures the 'default' service account exists, which can be referenced by pods that don't explicitly specify a service account.\n\nTOKEN GENERATION FLOW: The token generation pipeline (pkg/serviceaccount/claims.go and legacy.go) provides the Claims() function which creates JWT claims containing the service account identity, and optionally binds tokens to specific pods, secrets, or nodes. The LegacyClaims() function provides backward compatibility for legacy secret-based tokens. Both claim types are used by generateTokenIfNeeded() to create the actual JWT token string stored in the secret.\n\nPOD SPEC VALIDATION: The automountServiceAccountToken field is defined in pkg/apis/core/types.go for both PodSpec (allowing per-pod override) and ServiceAccount (setting namespace-wide default). The admission controller's Validate() method also enforces that pods have a valid service account reference and validates secret references based on the service account's mounted secrets list.\n\nThe complete pipeline ensures that: (1) pods automatically receive mounted service account tokens unless explicitly disabled, (2) tokens are stored as Kubernetes secrets, (3) token data is generated and managed automatically, and (4) service accounts exist in all namespaces."
}

